VLAN - VIRTUAL LOCAL AREA NETWORK
==================================
LAN 	- GROUP OF DEVICES WHERE LOCALLY CABLED
VLAN	- GROUP OF DEVICES WHERE ALL DEVICES RECEIVES BROADCAST
		- NETWORK ADDRESS
		- LOGICALLY DIVIDE NETWORK INTO DIFFERENT BROADCAST DOMAINS BY INFORMING THE SWITCH WHAT ARE THE GROUPS OF DEVICES IN YOUR NETWROK AND WHICH PORT DOES THESE DEVICES IS CONNECTED TO IN ITS INTERFACES.
		- EVERY GROUP IS A DIFFERENT DOMAIN



52 VLANs Fundamentals
=======================
VLAN- Virtual Local Area networks (LAN) 
- segmenting of broadcast domains to improve security and increase network efficiency.
- VLANs are used to virtually or logically divide or segment devices into different broadcast domain.
- VLANS are configure to Switch to be able to forward broadcast to devices within the same broadcast domain or within the same subnet address.
- We can be group broadcast by Switch interfaces.

	Ex. 	HR 	fa0/4,fa0/5, fa0/6 	- broadcast domain
	 	IT 	fa0/7, fa0/8, fa0/9 	- broadcast domain
		SALES 	fa0/7, fa0/8, fa0/9 	- broadcast domain


SWITCH: layer 2: LAN:
1. Broadcast
2. Network Address
	HR: 192.168.10.0/24
	IT: 192.168.20.0/24
	SALES: 192.168.30.0/24


Types of Switches
1. Managed - like Cisco
2. Unmanaged - Plug and Play

Switch default:
1. one port/interface equals one collision domain
2. One big broadcast domain


In Switch perspective

LAN - is a group of end devices interconnected by a switch located in a physical location.
LAN is a Broadcast Domain.
LAN is also a network or subnet address; therefore, network or subnet address is also a broadcast address. 
End Devices must be in the same subnet to receives each other's broadcast.

Broadcast Message = is a frame with destination MAC address of FFFF.FFFF.FFFF
Switch forwards frames based on MAC Address and to all its active interfaces.


Steps to Create VLANs
1. Create the Vlan # and Vlan Name
	SW(config)#vlan 10
	SW(config)#name HR
	SW(config)#exit
	
2. Assign ports to Vlans - take not of the 2 types of switchport modes (trunk and access)
	SW(config)#int fa0/2 or use the int range int fa0/3 - 6
	SW(config)#switchport mode access
	SW(config)#switchport access vlan 10
	SW(config)#exit




SWITCH DEFAULT:
------------------
- ONE PORT /INTERFACE = ONE COLLISION DOMAIN, one port/interface equals one collision domain
- Switch is ONE BIG BROADCAST DOMAIN - floods all the port with the broadcast message, One big broadcast domain
- SWITCH IS A LAYER 2 DEVICE that FORWARD PACKET BASED ON MAC ADDRESS (SOURCE/DSRTINATION)
